import BlogPost from '../../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import { getPost, nextPostFor } from '../../../data/posts';

const post = getPost('experiencia-somatica')!;
const locale = 'en';
---

<BlogPost
  locale={locale}
  title={post.en.title}
  description={post.en.description}
  altPath={`/blog/${locale === "es" ? post.slugEn : post.slugEs}/`}
  category={post.en.category}
  heroImage={post.heroImage}
  heroAlt={post.heroAlt.en}
  heroPosition={post.heroPosition}
  disqusIdentifier={post.en.disqusIdentifier}
  nextPost={nextPostFor(post.id, locale)}
>
  <p data-reveal>There's a question that comes up often when I talk to someone who's spent time in therapy without feeling that anything truly shifts: "If I already know where this comes from, why do I keep reacting the same way?" It's an honest question, and it deserves an equally honest answer: because intellectual knowing and the nervous system are two different things, and conventional therapy sometimes only speaks to one of the two.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Somatic Experiencing (SE) was developed by Peter Levine precisely to work with what's left out of the conversation.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>Why the nervous system gets "stuck"</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Levine arrived at his model by observing something deceptively simple: animals in the wild don't develop chronic trauma, despite being constantly exposed to life-or-death situations. A gazelle chased by a predator activates a massive physiological response — the nervous system mobilizes all available energy to flee or fight. If it escapes, it does something we rarely do: it shakes. It trembles. That involuntary movement discharges the energy mobilized for defense, and the cycle completes. Afterward, the gazelle goes back to grazing.</p>
  <p data-reveal>Humans have an extra layer: the prefrontal cortex, capable of inhibiting instinctive responses. And on top of that, culture — the expectation to stay in control, not to shake, not to "lose it." In moments of intense threat, the nervous system activates the same response as the gazelle. But then we stop it. Shame, dissociation, the internal command to "just calm down" interrupt the discharge before it completes.</p>
  <p data-reveal>That's trauma at the somatic level: not so much the event that occurred, but the response the body began and never finished. That energy doesn't disappear — it stays held in the nervous system, ready to activate at any cue that even remotely resembles the original threat. Bessel van der Kolk puts it bluntly: the body keeps the score, even when the mind has built distance from the memory.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>How SE completes what was left unfinished</h2>
  <p data-reveal>Somatic Experiencing doesn't work by reliving trauma. That's important to understand, because many people fear that talking about what happened means reliving it with the same intensity. SE works differently.</p>
  <p data-reveal>The central principle is <em>titration</em>: working in small doses of activation, not in a flood. Instead of going straight to the core of the trauma, the work begins by touching the edges — mild sensations, peripheral images, the beginning of a response before it becomes overwhelming. This keeps the nervous system from being overrun and allows something new to happen within a tolerable window.</p>
  <p data-reveal>The other principle is <em>pendulation</em>: moving rhythmically between activation and resource. A resource is anything — an image, a sensation in the body, a memory of safety — that anchors the nervous system in the present and in calm. When there's enough resource, the system can approach activation a little more without falling into panic or dissociation. This back-and-forth movement, repeated with patience, gradually expands the nervous system's capacity to tolerate and process what was previously too much.</p>
  <p data-reveal>What's ultimately sought is for the interrupted action impulse to find a place to complete itself. Sometimes that looks like a very small movement — a hand gently pushing, a sensation of extension in the legs — that the nervous system recognizes as the conclusion of the cycle. After that, something settles. People frequently describe feeling more weight in the body, more ground, more calm. Not because they "worked hard," but because the organism finally did what it wanted to do.</p>

  <h2 data-reveal>What this looks like in session</h2>
  <p data-reveal>My training in SE is deeply shaped by Lael Keen, whose work integrates the somatic terrain with layers of energy and character that go beyond the immediate survival response. That gives the work a dimension that isn't only technical — there's an understanding of the body as a field of personal, family, and existential history.</p>
  <p data-reveal>In session, work with SE is notably slow and detailed. I might ask you to pay attention to a specific sensation — a tightness in the chest, a tingling in the arms — and simply observe it without trying to change it. That act of observing with curiosity, without judgment, is already therapeutic. The nervous system responds differently when there's a witness than when it's alone with the experience.</p>
  <p data-reveal>SE sometimes works hand in hand with <a href="/en/blog/internal-family-systems/" class="link-underline">Internal Family Systems (IFS)</a>: identifying which internal <em>part</em> is carrying the fear response or chronic tension can give us more precise access to that part's somatic experience. Stephen Porges's <a href="/en/blog/polyvagal-theory/" class="link-underline">Polyvagal Theory</a> is an indispensable complementary map — understanding whether the nervous system is in social connection, mobilization, or collapse mode completely changes how I intervene in each moment. And when the work needs to reach deeper layers of character and energetic structure, I integrate it with <a href="/en/blog/core-energetics/" class="link-underline">Core Energetics</a>.</p>
  <p data-reveal>The radical premise of SE — and the one that resonates with me most — is that the body already knows how to heal. There's nothing to install, no truth to deliver from outside. The therapeutic work accompanies what the organism already wants to complete. There's something deeply respectful in that: the idea that you're not broken, but interrupted. And that with the right conditions, the movement toward wholeness happens naturally.</p>
  <p data-reveal>If you'd like to understand the general framework I work from, you can read about <a href="/en/blog/what-to-expect/" class="link-underline">what to expect from therapy</a> or about <a href="/en/blog/first-session/" class="link-underline">what a first session is like</a>. And if you recognize yourself in what's described here, it might be a good time to <a href="/en/blog/good-time-to-start/" class="link-underline">ask yourself when to begin</a>.</p>
</BlogPost>
